<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910826-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>910826-0055.</DOCID><HL>   Technology Brief -- Mentor Graphics Corp.:   Software Tool Firm Plans   To Fire 15% of Work Force</HL><DATE>08/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><CO>   MENT</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)OREGON (ORG)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Mentor Graphics Corp. said it will fire about 400 people,or 15% of its work force, resulting in a one-time charge ofup to $12 million.   Mentor, a maker of software tools used to designintegrated circuits, said costs associated with the firingswill cause a write-off of between $7 million and $12 millionin the third quarter.</LP><TEXT>   A spokeswoman wouldn't comment on whether the Wilsonville,Ore., company expected to post a net loss for the quarter.However, she said the third quarter is traditionally a slowone for the company. For the first six months, Mentor posteda net loss of $14.5 million, or 34 cents a share.   In the 1990 third quarter, Mentor reported net income of$3.7 million, or eight cents a share, on revenue of $101million.   Mentor said the firings -- the company's first -- willresult in savings of between $20 million and $30 million ayear. The spokeswoman said &quot;every group, across the board&quot;will be affected by the staffing reductions. As part of itsrestructuring, Mentor said it will substantially reduce itsinternal development of computer-aided software engineering,mechanical design and documentation products. It also plansto consolidate some field operations.</TEXT></DOC>